title: Mooy claims bragging rights over Socceroo
text:
Aaron Mooy’s Huddersfield march on against Massimo Luongo’s QPR AAP February 12, 2017 1:38pm 
AARON Mooy will take Championship bragging rights into Socceroos camp next month after his Huddersfield side consolidated third place in England’s second tier with a 2-1 win away to Massimo Luongo’s QPR. 
Luongo also received a yellow card late in the match for a challenge on Huddersfield’s Philip Billing and may just hear more about the result when the Socceroos face Iraq away on March 23 before hosting UAE five days later in Sydney. 
Mooy’s side sit seven points behind Newcastle, who returned to the top with a 1-0 win over Wolves after Brighton had briefly ascended to the summit with their 4-1 win over Burton Albion. 
Huddersfield took control in London with first-half goals from Izzy Brown and Nahki Wells. 
Substitute Luke Freeman netted on the hour mark with his first Rangers goal, but the visitors held on for a fourth consecutive league win and their first ever at Loftus Road. media_camera Aaron Mooy. 
On-loan Chelsea youngster Brown, who also scored against QPR while on loan at Rotherham earlier in the season, struck on 26 minutes. 
A slick move culminated in Wells crossing low from the left for Brown to score from close range - the 20-year-old midfielder’s fourth goal in six starts since joining Huddersfield. 
And the impressive Wells doubled the lead after another fine move 10 minutes later, rifling a right-footed shot into the far corner from right-hand side of the penalty area. 
Freeman, recently signed from Bristol City, hauled Rangers back into the game eight minutes after coming off the bench. media_camera Massimo Luongo. 
Huddersfield were unable to clear Kazenga LuaLua’s cross from the left and when the ball dropped to Freeman 20 yards out, he fired home. 
QPR were very much second best up to that point, although Conor Washington had almost given them an early lead. 
After some neat Rangers link-up play, Grant Hall slipped the ball through to Washington, whose shot was tipped on to the post by keeper Danny Ward. Elsewhere, Norwich thrashed Nottingham Forest 5-1. Leeds suffered an upset 2-1 loss to Cardiff, Derby and Bristol drew 3-3, Rotherham and Blackburn 1-1 and it was scoreless between Reading and Barnsley. 
Preston North End, Ipswich and Fulham all recorded wins over Brentford, Aston Villa and Wigan respectively.
